{"parse":{"title":"Terentius et delusor","pageid":17124444,"revid":847036038,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>Terentius et delusor</b></i><sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> is an anonymous poetical treatise, variously described as a <a href=\"/wiki/Dialogue\" title=\"Dialogue\">dialogue</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-segal_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-segal-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> or <a href=\"/wiki/Drama\" title=\"Drama\">spoken play</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-dronkexvii_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-dronkexvii-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> preserved only in fragments in a twelfth-century manuscript. It is the earliest example of the author or presenter of a play appearing as a person in the work, and in this case both appear: <a href=\"/wiki/Terence\" title=\"Terence\">Terence</a> and the (critical) theatrical producer (<i>persona delusoris</i>). The poem was probably acted or recited before a performance of one of Terence's works.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> It has been dated to the fifth century,<sup id=\"cite_ref-segal_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-segal-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> the seventh,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> between the seventh and eleventh,<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> the ninth or tenth century,<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Carolingian_Renaissance\" title=\"Carolingian Renaissance\">Carolingian Renaissance</a> (ninth century).<sup id=\"cite_ref-dronkexvii_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-dronkexvii-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The piece often finds mention beside <a href=\"/wiki/Roswitha\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Roswitha\">Roswitha</a>, who composed Christian dramas in Terentian style.\n</p><p>The plot of the brief performance piece is that the producer criticises Terence's plays as boring and out of style. Terence then proceeds to defend his work, probably ultimately submitting it to the judgement of the audience, who then viewed a performance of one of his plays. The play was probably mimed while the Terence character recited it, \"in the manner thought to be characteristic of actual Roman performances.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> The short piece testifies, however, to the lack of certainty about ancient practice. <i>An sit prosaicum nescio an metricum</i> says the producer about the drama of <a href=\"/wiki/Plautus\" title=\"Plautus\">Plautus</a>: \"we do not know whether they may be prose or meter.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><i>Terentius et delusor</i> was given its first modern edition, with annotations, by <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Magnin\" title=\"Charles Magnin\">Charles Magnin</a> in the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Biblioth%C3%A8que_de_l%27%C3%89cole_des_Chartes\" title=\"Biblioth\u00e8que de l&#39;\u00c9cole des Chartes\">Biblioth\u00e8que de l'\u00c9cole des Chartes</a></i> (vol. 1:1839&#8211;40, pp.&#160;517&#8211;535), where he titled it \"Fragment d'un comique in\u00e9dit du septi\u00e8me si\u00e8cle\" (Fragment of an unedited comedy of the seventh century). Next, Paul von Winterfeld edited the poem for <i>Hrotsvithae Opera</i>, xx&#8211;xxiii, in <a href=\"/wiki/Monumenta_Germaniae_Historica\" title=\"Monumenta Germaniae Historica\">MGH SS rerum Germanicarum</a> (Berlin: 1902). An updated version was made by Karl Strecker for MGH, <i>Poetae Latini aevi Carolini</i>, IV, 1088&#8211;90, in 1923 and for <i>Hrotsvithae Opera</i> in 1930. It has since appeared (without translation) in Appendix V, 326&#8211;328, of volume II of E. K. Chambers' <i>The Medieval Stage</i>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Terentius_et_delusor&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r853264625\">.mw-parser-output .refbegin{font-size:90%;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul{list-style-type:none;margin-left:0}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul>li,.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>dl>dd{margin-left:0;padding-left:3.2em;text-indent:-3.2em;list-style:none}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-100{font-size:100%}</style><div class=\"refbegin\" style=\"\">\n<ul><li>Chambers, Edmund Kerchever (1903). <i>The Mediaeval Stage</i>, 2 vols. Oxford. <small><a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-486-29229-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-486-29229-0\">0-486-29229-0</a>.</small></li>\n<li>Dronke, Peter (1984). <i>Women Writers of the Middle Ages: A Critical Study of Texts from Perpetua (+203) to Marguerite Porete (+1310)</i>. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li>\n<li>Dronke, Peter, ed. and trans. (1994). <i>Nine Medieval Latin Plays</i>. Cambridge Medieval Classics I. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. <small><a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-521-39537-2\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-521-39537-2\">0-521-39537-2</a>.</small></li>\n<li>Segal, Erich (2001). <i>The Death of Comedy</i>. Harvard University Press. <small><a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-674-01247-X\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-674-01247-X\">0-674-01247-X</a>.</small></li>\n<li>Tydeman, William (1978). <i>The Theatre in the Middle Ages: Western European Stage Conditions c. 800&#8211;1576</i>. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li>\n<li>Manso, Francisco Nodar (1990). <i>Teatro Menor Galaico-Portugu\u00e9s (Siglo XIII): Reconstrucci\u00f3n Contextual y Teor\u00eda del Discurso</i>. Edition Reichenberger. <small><a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/3-923593-95-3\" title=\"Special:BookSources/3-923593-95-3\">3-923593-95-3</a>.</small></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Marcelino_Men%C3%A9ndez_y_Pelayo\" title=\"Marcelino Men\u00e9ndez y Pelayo\">Men\u00e9ndez y Pelayo, Marcelino</a>. <a class=\"external text\" href=\"http://es.wikisource.org/wiki/La_Celestina:_Razones_para_tratar_de_esta_obra_dram%C3%A1tica_en_la_historia_de_la_novela_espa%C3%B1ola\"><i>La Celestina: Razones para tratar de esta obra dram\u00e1tica en la historia de la novela espa\u00f1ola</i>.</a> Buenos Aires: Espasa-Calpe, 1947.</li>\n<li>Ogilvy, J. D. A. (1963). \"<i>Mimi</i>, <i>Scurrae</i>, <i>Histriones</i>: Entertainers of the Early Middle Ages.\" <i><a href=\"/wiki/Speculum_(journal)\" title=\"Speculum (journal)\">Speculum</a></i>, <b>38</b>:4 (October), pp.&#160;603&#8211;619.</li></ul>\n</div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Terentius_et_delusor&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Translated \"Terence and the Heckler\" by Erich Segal and \"Altercation between Terence and his Critic\" by Peter Dronke.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-segal-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-segal_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-segal_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Segal, 221.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-dronkexvii-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-dronkexvii_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-dronkexvii_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Dronke, <i>Nine Medieval Latin Plays</i>, xvii.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Ogilvy, 619.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Dronke, <i>Women Writers of the Middle Ages</i>, 58, notes that there are directions for movement (<i>nunc Terentius exit foras audiens haec et ait</i>, \"now Terence comes out, hearing this, and says\"), for asides to the audience, and for impersonation, all implying performance. This would have been less like a \"staged\" play and more like a <i>scenica lectio</i> (acted reading), which was known in the twelfth century as a method of \"doing\" Terence.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Magnin, according to Men\u00e9ndez y Pelayo, chapt. 7.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Chambers, 85.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Manso, 116.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Manso, 116, quoting Tydeman, 26.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-10\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Men\u00e9ndez y Pelayo, chapt. 7; Segal, 221.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1244\nCached time: 20180911110159\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.092 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.130 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 1149/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 5020/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 1709/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 15/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 3931/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.012/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 981 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  108.870      1 -total\n 40.28%   43.850      4 Template:ISBN\n 21.01%   22.877      1 Template:Italic_title\n 16.53%   17.994      1 Template:Reflist\n 15.56%   16.937      4 Template:Catalog_lookup_link\n 13.45%   14.647      1 Template:Refbegin\n  8.12%    8.845      4 Template:Error-small\n  6.34%    6.904     12 Template:Yesno-no\n  4.22%    4.597      1 Template:Column-width\n  4.08%    4.437     12 Template:Yesno\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:17124444-0!canonical and timestamp 20180911110159 and revision id 847036038\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"Terentius Et Delusor","*":"Medieval_drama"},{"sortkey":"Terentius Et Delusor","*":"Early_medieval_Latin_literature"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Biblioth\u00e8que de l'\u00c9cole des Chartes"},{"ns":0,"exists":"",